The Seven Shade Arches are heat-shelter and passage-control structures embedded in Scorching Sands route doctrine.
They mark the seven recognized rest points along the primary transit corridor through the Scorching Sands, spaced at maximum safe travel intervals for daytime heat.
Each arch is a stone structure wide enough to shelter a small caravan from direct sun during peak hours, oriented to cast shadow in the direction of the afternoon sun.
The arches were constructed during the Keeper of Measure survey era as functional infrastructure, not ceremonial — each bears a gnomon slot aligned for shadow measurement at the local noon.
Route doctrine mandates that caravans approaching the Scorching Sands from any direction establish their position relative to the nearest arch before committing to daylight transit.
Arches are numbered first to seventh from east to west, though local oral tradition also names them after the seven states of water: mist, dew, ice, spring, flow, flood, and still.
The fourth arch — "flow" — sits at the geographic center and is the only one with a cistern depression beneath it, fed by an ancient filtration channel now mostly silted.
Reaver groups in the Scorching Sands treat the arches as territorial markers rather than neutral shelter; which arches are safely accessible changes seasonally.
The Jackal Synod maintains a presence at the third arch, offering water blessings in exchange for tribute — an arrangement that legitimate caravans navigate cautiously.
Sand-Sea Carters' Guild routes explicitly plan around arch availability rather than straight-line distance.
The arches are old enough that their builder identity is contested; Keeper survey marks, older stonework, and at least one arch with pre-Keeper measurement notation coexist on their surfaces.

